Please forgive my elementary knowledge :) A good habit to source answers nonetheless, thanks!"},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/524b971da79aab662e1fc04926c2b050?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":1300,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/1300/nick","reputation":305,"display_name":"Nick"},"score":0,"post_id":3264,"edited":false,"creation_date":1345814427,"comment_id":4958,"body":"Also remember that it is not Na+/K+ ions which go through the ion channels, but the solvated ions which are encased in a highly ordered water solvation sphere around them. The different sized sovlation spheres is what causes the difference in sizes for the ion channels. In a cell, negative ions would screen the positive charges from each other unless they were very close."}],"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1345565843,"creation_date":1345531567,"body":"<p>The carriers of the charge are ions and they get repelled from each other well enough. Other than their charge there is only the size in which they differ (for all practical purposes). This means, as long as we are talking about membrane potential, the actors are just a mix of 1+ ions which don't come near each other. When size matters, for example in an ion channel, we are talking about single particles, so there is no action of a repulsive force between K+ and Na+.<\/p>\n\n<p>From another angle: The charge is a force that emerges from a sea of particles, regardless if they are all of one kind or mixed K+/Na+. If you talk about a force between K+ and Na+ then you would have to separate all 10^15 or so K+ ions from 10^15 or so Na+ ions which is simply impossible, as they are mixed up.<\/p>\n\n<p><a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Brownian_motion\" rel=\"nofollow\">http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Brownian_motion<\/a><\/p>\n\n<p><a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ion\" rel=\"nofollow\">http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ion<\/a><\/p>\n\n<p><a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ion_channel\" rel=\"nofollow\">http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ion_channel<\/a><\/p>\n","answer_id":3264,"question_id":3262,"up_vote_count":7,"last_edit_date":1345565843}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/3262/why-isnt-there-any-repulsive-force-between-na-and-k-disrupting-thier-roles-in","last_activity_date":1345566656,"creation_date":1345526979,"answer_count":1,"title":"Why isn't there any repulsive force between Na+ and K+ disrupting thier roles in transmembrane voltage/ action potentials","body":"<p>Pretty self explanatory question. I have a basic grasp on the \"How\" and \"Why\" of Reversal/Action Potential in and between neurons, but this question lingers.<\/p>\n","question_id":3262,"tags":["biochemistry","electrophysiology","intracellular-transport"],"score":4,"accepted_answer_id":3264,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":100,"up_vote_count":4,"last_edit_date":1345566656},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/2bfb7772ecd4b602a96302e52c5bc380?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":1186,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/1186/aditya-chawla","reputation":121,"display_name":"Aditya Chawla"},"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/1c4c93f2f4aa4c5d4861c55ade5dc790?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":1197,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/1197/darlingtonia","reputation":341,"display_name":"Darlingtonia"},"score":0,"post_id":3259,"edited":false,"creation_date":1345498535,"comment_id":4878,"body":"The Wikipedia &quot;Enzyme Assay&quot; page looks pretty good."}],"answers":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/b510e9cb741e4f4e1aed1c4642f21066?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":1250,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/1250/conner","reputation":604,"display_name":"Conner"},"score":5,"is_accepted":false,"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1345501112,"creation_date":1345498469,"body":"<p>This refers to the <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Turnover_number\">turnover number<\/a> (a.k.a k<sub>cat<\/sub> or k<sub>2<\/sub>) of an enzyme and is usually calculated using <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Michaelis-Menten_kinetics\">Michaelis-Menten<\/a> kinetics. Jump to the summary at the end if you want a simple answer. If you want a more thorough answer, consider the following chemical equation:<\/p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>[E] + [S] ⇌ [ES] → [E] + [P]<\/p>\n<\/blockquote>\n\n<p>This says that a certain concentration of enzyme mixed with a certain concentration of substrate will first combine and form a complex depending on the enzyme's <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Affinity\">affinity<\/a> for the substrate. Then the enzyme complex will generate a product depending on the enzyme's ability to convert the transition state into product. The k<sub>1<\/sub> constant is the arrow moving from [E] + [S] → [ES] and the k<sub>-1<\/sub> is the arrow moving from [ES] → [E] + [S] (they oppose each other). The k<sub>2<\/sub> constant is the arrow moving from [ES] → [E] + [P].<\/p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>V<sub>o<\/sub> = [ES]k<sub>2<\/sub><\/p>\n<\/blockquote>\n\n<ul>\n<li>V<sub>o<\/sub> - this is the rate that product is being formed, which can be measured.<\/li>\n<li>[ES] - this is the concentration of enzyme-substrate complexes.<\/li>\n<li>k<sub>2<\/sub> - this is a constant value comparing the two.<\/li>\n<\/ul>\n\n<p>This can also be expressed in terms of maximum rate:<\/p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>V<sub>max<\/sub> = [E]<sub>T<\/sub>k<sub>2<\/sub><\/p>\n<\/blockquote>\n\n<ul>\n<li>V<sub>max<\/sub> - V<sub>max<\/sub> is catalytic rate when [E]<sub>T<\/sub> = [ES] (when all of the enzyme present is bound to substrate/saturated).<\/li>\n<li>[E]<sub>T<\/sub> - [E]<sub>T<\/sub> is the total enzyme concentration. [E]<sub>T<\/sub> = [E] + [ES].<\/li>\n<li>k<sub>2<\/sub> - the k<sub>cat<\/sub> is the catalytic constant. It is a constant indicating how quickly an enzyme can convert substrates into products. It is easily observed by this equation.<\/li>\n<\/ul>\n\n<h3>Summary<\/h3>\n\n<p>So k<sub>2<\/sub> is basically an indicator of how efficiently or quickly an enzyme operates. Not all enzymes follow standard <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Michaelis-Menten_kinetics\">Michaelis-Menten<\/a> kinetics. For example, the <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Allosteric_regulation\">allosteric properties<\/a> of some enzymes cause a non-linear saturation curve. Because of this, the turnover number is commonly referred to. The turnover number's units of s<sup>-1<\/sup> indicate one product molecule per second, so a turnover rate of 3000 means you can create 3000 products in 1 second at V<sub>max<\/sub>.<\/p>\n","answer_id":3261,"question_id":3259,"up_vote_count":5,"last_edit_date":1345501112}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/3259/what-are-the-units-of-enzyme-activity","last_activity_date":1345501112,"creation_date":1345491303,"answer_count":1,"title":"What are the units of enzyme activity?","body":"<p>I was looking at <a href=\"http://www.uic.edu/classes/bios/bios100/labs/graph05.jpg\">this<\/a> graph of turnip <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Peroxidase\">peroxidase<\/a> activity and I saw that they use units of 1/sec for enzyme activity. What does this unit intuitively represent and how is it calculated?<\/p>\n","question_id":3259,"tags":["biochemistry","enzymes"],"score":5,"down_vote_count":1,"is_answered":true,"view_count":552,"up_vote_count":6,"last_edit_date":1345496873},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/ed18d392c11d9d4e10c542289e367cae?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":223,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/223/gkadam","reputation":911,"display_name":"gkadam","accept_rate":38},"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/8729233d525a654914051bf8c1234c78?s=128&d=identicon&r=