 any inherited genomic data that the hybrid label would be appropriate.<\/p>\n","answer_id":3240,"question_id":3238,"up_vote_count":3}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/3238/can-an-organism-obtaining-a-part-of-its-genome-via-horizontal-gene-transfer-be-c","last_activity_date":1345371964,"creation_date":1345324162,"answer_count":1,"title":"Can an organism obtaining a part of its genome via horizontal gene transfer be called a \"hybrid\"?","body":"<p>Wikipedia definition of \"<a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hybrid_%28biology%29\" rel=\"nofollow\">hybrid<\/a>\" offers many competing definitions. But most seem to be centered on sexual-reproduction gene transfer.<\/p>\n\n<p>Is there an official (in a textbook or widely accepted peer reviewed work) definition of a \"hybrid\"/\"hybridization\" that would clearly include ANY genetic mixing, <strong>most specifically obtaining genes via horizontal gene transfer<\/strong>?<\/p>\n\n<p>If not, is it specifically because \"hybrid\" requires sexual reproduction, or merely because it requires a certain minimal amount of inherited genetic material from both sides, and horisontal genetic transfer in practice involves significantly less genetic material being inherited?<\/p>\n","question_id":3238,"tags":["genetics","horizontal-gene-transfer","definitions"],"score":7,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":73,"up_vote_count":7,"last_edit_date":1345371964},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/08613e0b782cdf2bb8f2501cae9bdc5d?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":806,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/806/armatus","reputation":5317,"display_name":"Armatus","accept_rate":81},"answers":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/b510e9cb741e4f4e1aed1c4642f21066?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":1250,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/1250/conner","reputation":604,"display_name":"Conner"},"score":