n the cytoplasm of the rod and is necessary for the continued operation of the sodium channel sending the neural signal.<\/p>\n\n<p>In the dark, the channel is open and the Rods are active. In bright light, due to the amplification from cascade effects, all of the channels will be closed, stopping the Rods from sending their normal signals until cGMP levels are able to compensate.<\/p>\n\n<p>My guess is that the bleaching ceases fairly quickly and the proteins return to their original conforms shortly, but it's the cGMP levels (remember, cGMP is destroyed, so any new cGMP replacing the old must be synthesized first) that take a long time to recover as the signal to destroy the cGMP initiates a cascade that results in strong amplifications.<\/p>\n","answer_id":3190,"question_id":3188,"up_vote_count":3}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/3188/why-do-rod-cells-not-recover-after-bleaching-upon-exposure-to-bright-light","last_activity_date":1345157368,"creation_date":1345086712,"answer_count":1,"title":"Why do rod cells not recover after bleaching upon exposure to bright light?","body":"<p>I'm confused as to why, when exposed to bright light, rod cells cease to function.<\/p>\n\n<p>I understand that exposure to bright light bleaches all of the rhodopsin, but...so what?<\/p>\n\n<p>Why doesn't the bleached product (opsonin/retinal) simply get re-synthesised back into rhodopsin as it does in dim light, and therefore continue the cycle and enable impulses?<\/p>\n","question_id":3188,"tags":["human-biology","eyes"],"score":5,"accepted_answer_id":3190,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":849,"up_vote_count":5,"last_edit_date":1345132967},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/562621b3ad7b8da35e6a4667ce82272f?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":1176,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/1176/chirag","reputation":239,"display_name":"Chirag"},"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.grav