andom sites of normal\n  skin in humans and animals. This reinforces that a latent life cycle\n  is often a characteristic of these viruses.<\/p>\n<\/blockquote>\n\n<p><strong>Interesting Notes<\/strong><\/p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>There are no known PVs that infect more than one species.<\/li>\n<li>To date, about 100 different types of HPVs have been fully characterized.<\/li>\n<li>Human PVs does not grow on conventional culture media. The diagnosis of HPV infection is made by histopathology of lesions<\/li>\n<\/ul>\n","answer_id":3175,"question_id":3160,"up_vote_count":4}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/3160/what-is-the-life-cycle-of-a-wart","last_activity_date":1345053362,"creation_date":1344893996,"answer_count":2,"title":"What is the life cycle of a wart?","body":"<p>There doesn't seem to be a lot of information available on research done on warts.  What is the life cycle of a wart?  How does it spread? -- specifically how does it recruit cells to spread it?  What is the life cycle of a PV-infected dermal cell? <\/p>\n","question_id":3160,"tags":["virology","pathology"],"score":8,"accepted_answer_id":3162,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":5895,"up_vote_count":8,"last_edit_date":1345053362},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/8e78e7e5a7e4051632e25537023aeacd?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":99,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/99/richard-terrett","reputation":641,"display_name":"Richard Terrett"},"answers":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/889548c1e8387b3d381853dee5212cfd?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":3632,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/3632/shigeta","reputation":22684,"display_name":"shigeta","accept_rate":86},"score":4,"is_accepted":false,"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1345002762,"creation_date":1344958947,"body":"<p>I think I found a reference.  Most of these papers are behind paywalls - its a pretty obscure topic in biology, though not because it isn't interesting...<\/p>\n\n<p>For those not familiar with the question, the thylakoid membranes are an organelle structure in the <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chloroplast\" rel=\"nofollow\">chloroplast<\/a>, which contains all the photosynthetic machinery in the plant cell.  The chloroplast is though to be a symbiotic cyanobacterium captured to make eukaryotic plants.  Like mitochondria, the chloroplast maintains its own chromosome and some ribosomal machinery. <\/p>\n\n<p>The stack (grana) and extended (stromal lamallae) structures of the thylakoid no doubt help optimize light/energy capture by distributing the light gathering proteins in an advantageous way.  It was previously believed that the electrostatic charge of the thylakoid membrane helped make the stacks, but this <a href=\"http://jfallen.org/~john/webstar/john/pdf/124.pdf\" rel=\"nofollow\">Trends in Plant Science review article (Allen and Forsberg, 2001)<\/a> discusses how the distribution of photosystem (PS) I and II are more concentrated in the stroma and grana respectively.  <\/p>\n\n<p>They put forth that Light Harvesting complex II (LHC II), which gathers photons for PSII tends to cluster in a trans fashion - forming contacts with LHCII in membranes above it, specifically forming the grana stacks enriched in PSII. <\/p>\n","answer_id":3172,"question_id":1833,"up_vote_count":4,"last_edit_date":1345002762}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/1833/does-a-theory-exist-for-the-formation-of-thylakoid-structure","last_activity_date":1345002762,"creation_date":1334553779,"answer_count":1,"title":"Does a theory exist for the formation of thylakoid structure?","body":"<p>I'm interested in how the structure of the <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Thylakoid\">thylakoid<\/a> forms into its characteristic highly rugose stacks of grana. What causes the thylakoid to invaginate and self-associate, albeit with what appear to be fairly large gaps in between folds?<\/p>\n","question_id":1833,"tags":["biochemistry","plant-physiology","cell-biology","photosynthesis"],"score":13,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":123,"up_vote_count":13,"last_edit_date":1342757966},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/XDA2o.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":338,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/338/j-musser","reputation":1309,"display_name":"J. Musser","accept_rate":98},"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/ef067cf09ffd3cc8f069bacec73c8202?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":222,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/222/david-lebauer","reputation":780,"display_name":"David LeBauer","accept_rate":80},"score":0,"post_id":1489,"edited":false,"creation_date":1332371924,"comment_id":1889,"body":"Essentially the answer is yes, except that your qualification &quot;but it is not a perfect regeneration, and has no likeness in form to the previous stem.&quot; is confusing me - I would consider all stems from a single plant to share a likeness in form. No, they won&#39;t be identical, but neither is a regenerated limb identical to a lost limb."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/XDA2o.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":338,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/338/j-musser","reputation":1309,"display_name":"J. Musser","accept_rate":98},"score":0,"post_id":1489,"reply_to_user":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/ef067cf09ffd3cc8f069bacec73c8202?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":222,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/222/david-lebauer","reputation":780,"display_name":"David LeBauer","accept_rate":80},"edited":false,"creation_date":1332380922,"comment_id":1891,"body":"How about the leaves?"},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/ef067cf09ffd3cc8f069bacec73c8202?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG",