ontributing to the desired rate, or are you working with pure proteins from the three species? (ii) Have you looked at the kinetics? For example, if all 3 proteins have different Km (Michaelis Constant) values for ATP and you are using one fixed concentration of substrate which happens to be below the Km values (in all cases, say) this will give rise to different rates, but if the substrate conc is upped to 10X-Km (in all cases) you might find no difference in rates!"},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/2bfb7772ecd4b602a96302e52c5bc380?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":1186,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/1186/aditya-chawla","reputation":121,"display_name":"Aditya Chawla"},"score":0,"post_id":3051,"edited":false,"creation_date":1343657694,"comment_id":4502,"body":"(i) I used an NADH-PK Linked Assay where I looked at the absorbance decrease when NADH is oxidized to NAD+. They were all pure proteins. (see: NADH-coupled microplate photometric assay for kinetic studies of ATP-hydrolyzing enzymes with low and high specific activities) (ii) All the Km values were different, ranging from 2mM-4mM and I used ATP concentrations ranging from 0mM to 10mM."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/ed18d392c11d9d4e10c542289e367cae?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":223,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/223/gkadam","reputation":911,"display_name":"gkadam","accept_rate":38},"score":3,"post_id":3051,"edited":false,"creation_date":1343659757,"comment_id":4503,"body":"Have you checked sequence similarity/identity, especially of the nucleotide contacting regions (otherwise known as the P-loops I think)?"},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/2bfb7772ecd4b602a96302e52c5bc380?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":1186,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/1186/aditya-chawla","reputation":121,"display_name":"Aditya Chaw