<\/sup> allele as template.  I suspect over time as organisms became more complex and HEGs become unable to mobilize they would become fixed in the organisms genome.  Upon being fixed there is no selection pressure to maintain the open reading frame of the HEG or the intron its encoded within (<a href=\"http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0959437X04001571\">ref<\/a>).  This causes the eventual loss of the HEG and intron since they provide no real benefit to the organisms genome.<\/p>\n\n<p>I don't know how much of the yeast mitochondrial genome is taken up by these introns.  I believe that there are 4 of them in yeast some of the introns also require reverse transcriptase for splicing and mobility.  Other fungal species can have many more introns and sometimes weird things like introns embedded within introns.<\/p>\n","answer_id":1414,"question_id":1045,"up_vote_count":7,"last_edit_date":1331691457}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/1045/is-there-any-reason-for-the-variation-in-mitochondrial-dna-size","last_activity_date":1343344396,"creation_date":1329250340,"answer_count":2,"title":"Is there any reason for the variation in mitochondrial DNA size?","body":"<p>As my textbook <em>An Introduction to Genetic Analysis<\/em> points out, yeast mitochondrial DNA has approximately 78 kb of genetic data, while the human mitochondrial DNA contains 17 kb. Is there any evolution reason for this drastic change in size? Also, are there any particularities about mitochondrial function that have been compromised with this reduction in size?<\/p>\n\n<hr>\n\n<h2>References<\/h2>\n\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Griffiths, Anthony J. F.<\/strong> <em>An Introduction to Genetic Analysis.<\/em> New York: W.H. Freeman, 2000.<\/li>\n<\/ul>\n","question_id":1045,"tags":["evolution","genetics","physiology"],"score":12,"accepted_answer_id":1414,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":419,"up_vote_count":12,"last_edit_date":1343344396},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/5cff3e84bcedd40163c74d33b827ac7c?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":307,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/307/lancelafontaine","reputation":3814,"display_name":"LanceLafontaine","accept_rate":47},"answers":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/13f5a730dead005d0a3a947d3c09ab81?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":691,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/691/chm","reputation":553,"display_name":"CHM"},"score":6,"is_accepted":true,"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1333415654,"creation_date":1333415654,"body":"<p>You'd think if such devices were used in humans, they wouldn't require a change of lifestyle.<\/p>\n\n<p>They don't say the power <em>always<\/em> decreases over time:<\/p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>Katz\u2019s snails, for example, produced up to 7.45 microwatts, but after\n  45 minutes, that power had decreased by 80%. To draw continuous power,\n  Katz\u2019s team had to ramp down the power they extracted to 0.16\n  microwatts.<\/p>\n<\/blockquote>\n\n<p>This is really a chemistry question. The glucose has to be brought to the fuel cell some way. In this case, the glucose is oxydized directly in the hemolymph. As oxygen PP in the hemolymph is always greater than glucose concentration(1), your limiting rate (which is related to the power you can get from the device) is that of glucose intake <em>at the fuel cell<\/em>. Therefore, the more you oxidize glucose per unit time, the greater intake you need to keep the output from dropping.<\/p>\n\n<p>The glucose intake at the fuel cell is a function of biological parameters such as quantity eaten, metabolic efficiency, metabolic speed, blood flow, but also diffusion. The kinetics of glucose intake at the fuel cell are such that you can't ask for <em>too much<\/em> power for <em>too long<\/em>.<\/p>\n\n<p>I suggest you read the article to get a more detailed answer. Nature news is good, but there's nothing like reading the real paper.<\/p>\n\n<p><strong>1<\/strong> <a href=\"http://pubs.acs.org/doi/full/10.1021/ja211714w\">http://pubs.acs.org/doi/full/10.1021/ja211714w<\/a><\/p>\n","answer_id":1639,"question_id":1635,"up_vote_count":6},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/3bb465ba7c2338b41ef15a2a05306a7c?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":444,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/444/gianpaolo-r","reputation":3120,"display_name":"Gianpaolo R","accept_rate":40},"score":4,"is_accepted":false,"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1333732867,"creation_date":1333446090,"body":"<blockquote>\n  <p>Would this application in humans require that a patient eats more and \"breathes more\" than average? <\/p>\n<\/blockquote>\n\n<p>From the cellular standview, each glucose and O<sub>2<\/sub> molecule that you substract to the cell for use in a second futile cycle, should be replaced. However, I doubt that the amount of glucose/O<sub>2<\/sub> required per hour will be so important to require additional food intake.<\/p>\n\n<p>By the way, each cell in the body <strong>normally<\/strong> generates electricity from glucose and O<sub>2<\/sub>: just think at the electron transport chain during the mitochondrial cellular respiration.<\/p>\n","answer_id":1645,"question_id":1635,"up_vote_count":4,"last_edit_date":1333732867}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/1635/electricity-generated-by-the-body-and-its-applications","last_activity_date":1343344173,"creation_date":1333402717,"answer_count":2,"title":"Electricity generated by the body and its applications?","body":"<p>I recently came across <a href=\"http://www.nature.com/news/cyborg-snails-power-up-1.10210\" rel=\"nofollow\">this article<\/a> from Nature. In it, it states that the snails have \"tiny biofuel cells that extract electrical power from the glucose and oxygen in the snail\u2019s blood\", and that the power obtained is dependent on \"how quickly sugar and oxygen can be taken from the creatures' blood\". They go on to say that the power obtained decreases over time, and that these implants could power future pacemakers in humans. <\/p>\n\n<p>Would this application in humans require that a patient eats more and \"breathes more\" than average? Why does the power output decrease over time, and couldn't that potentially lead to the malfunctioning of a pacemaker?<\/p>\n\n<hr>\n\n<h2>References<\/h2>\n\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Van Noorden, Richard.<\/strong> <em>\u201cCyborg Snails Power Up.\u201d<\/em> Nature (March 12, 2012). <a href=\"http://www.nature.com/doifinder/10.1038/nature.2012.10210\" rel=\"nofollow\">http://www.nature.com/doifinder/10.1038/nature.2012.10210<\/a>.<\/li>\n<\/ul>\n","question_id":1635,"tags":["biotechnology"],"score":8,"accepted_answer_id":1639,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":224,"up_vote_count":8,"last_edit_date":1343344173},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/faeeef7d7a44f1007f2832d54f8e7e94?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":1005,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/1005/everyone","reputation":1798,"display_name":"Everyone","accept_rate":57},"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/ab24c0e23c30888c23e2d4fe9991cf2b?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":57,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/57/jonsca","reputation":3367,"display_name":"jonsca","accept_rate":100},"score":0,"post_id":3013,"edited":false,"creation_date":1343218087,"comment_id":4416,"body":"Aren&#39;t they all trees in the end, anyway?"},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/faeeef7d7a44f1007f2832d54f8e7e94?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":1005,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/1005/everyone","reputation":1798,"display_name":"Everyone","accept_rate":57},"score":0,"post_id":3013,"reply_to_user":{"profile_image":"https://www.grava