l becomes less important. (See <a href=\"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/2055/do-trees-age-on-a-microscopic-level/\" title=\"do trees age on a microscopic level\">biology.stackexchange.com/questions/2055/&hellip;<\/a> out of interest)"},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/5cff3e84bcedd40163c74d33b827ac7c?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":307,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/307/lancelafontaine","reputation":3814,"display_name":"LanceLafontaine","accept_rate":47},"score":1,"post_id":3013,"edited":false,"creation_date":1343334529,"comment_id":4452,"body":"Depending on what plant/tree is concerned, I could also imagine things like bark absorbing some of the radiation  being emitted."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/faeeef7d7a44f1007f2832d54f8e7e94?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":1005,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/1005/everyone","reputation":1798,"display_name":"Everyone","accept_rate":57},"score":0,"post_id":3013,"reply_to_user":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/9bbe3bd8b81991d8ccf5c6763edb1184?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":740,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/740/luke","reputation":4547,"display_name":"Luke","accept_rate":69},"edited":false,"creation_date":1343554559,"comment_id":4473,"body":"@Luke: The overall effect and any inheritable changes were what I had in mind."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/faeeef7d7a44f1007f2832d54f8e7e94?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":1005,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/1005/everyone","reputation":1798,"display_name":"Everyone","accept_rate":57},"score":0,"post_id":3013,"reply_to_user":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/5cff3e84bcedd40163c74d33b827ac7c?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":307,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.c