 a sample of the blood it is not uncommon to find fragments of DNA. These may well be from a parent or grandparent, but the DNA (as I understand it) is &#39;left over&#39; from (e.g.) an apoptosis event, rather than found in the host cells. It is also possible to find fragments of bacterial DNA in circulating blood, but this does not imply that the DNA has been incorporated into the hosts, and therefore no traits have been transferred."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/6fc641bdddde78a51c0db6b8527c54f7?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":172,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/172/polynomial","reputation":423,"display_name":"Polynomial","accept_rate":71},"score":0,"post_id":2914,"edited":false,"creation_date":1342536277,"comment_id":4233,"body":"I remember it mentioning increased risk of transfer of diseases, so I&#39;ll dig out the article tonight and post an excerpt."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/ab24c0e23c30888c23e2d4fe9991cf2b?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":57,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/57/jonsca","reputation":3367,"display_name":"jonsca","accept_rate":100},"score":0,"post_id":2914,"reply_to_user":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/6fc641bdddde78a51c0db6b8527c54f7?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":172,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/172/polynomial","reputation":423,"display_name":"Polynomial","accept_rate":71},"edited":false,"creation_date":1342582761,"comment_id":4248,"body":"@Polynomial I&#39;d be interested, too.  I did a fairly extensive search and only found a NS article on Marmosets from 2007.  Is that the one that you found?"},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/6fc641bdddde78a51c0db6b8527c54f7?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":172,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/172/polynomial","reputation":423,"displa