perm fertilizes the ovum which would than bring the chromosome number to to correct tally.  So combining the genetic material in two ovum should bring the chromosome count to the correct tally as well, but scientists would need to somehow motivate the  activities that happen when typical  sexual reproduction occurs. It's likely very challenging to do that if not highly improbable. Should it work, this process could only produce female children. <\/p>\n","answer_id":2854,"question_id":2853,"up_vote_count":3}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/2853/is-ovum-ovum-fertilization-possible-for-human","last_activity_date":1341963566,"creation_date":1341852476,"answer_count":1,"title":"Is ovum + ovum fertilization possible for human?","body":"<p>In humans is it possible to fertilize a ovum with another ovum from the same female subject? <\/p>\n\n<p>I already found some works in which the ovum is fertilized by a somatic cell (see e.g. <a href=\"http://news.sciencemag.org/sciencenow/2001/07/12-01.html\" rel=\"nofollow\"> this <\/a>), but I am looking for fertilization specifically by another ovum.<\/p>\n\n<p>Around a year ago I found in the internet a Japanese (ongoing) study on this, but cannot locate it any more. <\/p>\n\n<p>I would greatly appreciate any help. <\/p>\n","question_id":2853,"tags":["molecular-genetics","reproduction","human-genetics","cytogenetics"],"score":4,"down_vote_count":1,"is_answered":true,"view_count":2392,"up_vote_count":5},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/4130798b102651c9cd6b3ea83abb08c1?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":801,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/801/yoyostein","reputation":146,"display_name":"yoyostein"},"answers":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/e60c4ebf047734e923ffa4ffa45337cd?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":1122,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/1122/rwst","reputation":3115,"display_name":